SIMPLE: prepossess
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Prepossess
<hw>Pre`pos*sess"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.
& p. p.</pos> <conjf>Prepossessed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. &
vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Prepossessing</conjf>.]</vmorph>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To preoccupy, as ground or land; to take previous
possession of.</def> <rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To preoccupy, as the mind or heart, so as to
preclude other things; hence, to bias or prejudice; to give a previous
inclination to, for or against anything; esp., to induce a favorable
opinion beforehand, or at the outset.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It created him enemies, and <qex>prepossessed</qex> the lord
general.</q> <rj><qau>Evelyn.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Prepossessing</ent>⟦br⟧
